<DOC><DOCNO> AP880524-0119 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1121EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0545 05-24 0587</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,0600</SECOND><HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Rumble Along Middle Atlantic Coast</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs UPDATE with storm-related death in NorthCarolina, other details. Picks up in 9th graf, `In western ...'List of temperatures that normally appears at end of story isunavailable today, because of computer problems at the NationalWeather Service.</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms rumbled along the East Coast today, killing awoman in North Carolina and unleashing winds up to 72 mph that cutpower to as many as 55,000 homes in three states.   A Florida weatherman and a cameraman also were hurt by anexplosion in their van resulting from a strong wind.   Powerful thunderstorms hit the Middle Atlantic coast fromsoutheastern New York to Delaware; showers and thunderstormsextended from western Pennsylvania to eastern South Carolina.Scattered light showers fell across New England.   Showers and a few thunderstorms lingered over Alabama andMississippi, Arkansas, Kentucky, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio. A fewlight showers dampened Kansas and Oklahoma.   On Monday, fierce thunderstorms downed trees and power lines,knocking out electricity to 23,000 homes in the Baltimore area,9,000 homes in the Washington area and up to 23,000 homes in NorthCarolina, utility officials said.   In North Carolina, high winds blew the roofs off five apartmentbuildings in Burlington, forcing the evacuation of 50 people, saidthe Alamance County communications office.   A 37-year-old North Carolina woman was killed Monday night whenlightning struck a tree, severing a large limb that fell on thetruck she was driving.   Another woman was seriously hurt in a separate accident when hercar crashed during the storm, the state Highway Patrol reported.   At Piedmont Triad International Airport in the Winston-Salemarea, winds were clocked at 72 mph, just 2 mph below hurricanestrength.   In Jacksonville, Fla., a weatherman and a cameraman for a localTV station suffered burns when a gust of wind pushed the antenna ontheir remote-broadcast van into a power line.   The 24,000-volt charge surged through the van's wiring, causingelectrical equipment inside to explode, Paul Baldwin, news directorfor WLTV-TV Channel 12, said of the noontime Monday accident. Theaccident happened just after a live broadcast from the town ofAtlantic Beach.   Both men were listed in fair condition today.   In Demopolis, Ala., state troopers said small hail caused afive-car pileup with two minor injuries.   And in Centreville, Ala., the National Weather Service recordedhail the size of quarters, although no traffic problems or damagewere reported.   In western Maryland, stiff winds blew a porch roof off anapartment house near Cumberland, but no injuries were reported,State Police said. A house was flooded in Friendsville, andflooding stranded motorists or closed roads in northwest Baltimoreand Montgomery County near Washington.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms fromKentucky, Tennessee and Alabama to the Atlantic Coast states;scattered showers and thunderstorms in the lower Mississippi Valleyand eastern Oklahoma; and widely scattered thunderstorms fromnortheast Nevada into western Montana.   High temperatures were expected to be in the 70s or 80s in mostof the nation; 60s along the Pacific Coast and over the GreatLakes, the northern Ohio Valley and northern New England; 50sacross Upper Michigan; 90s over parts of Georgia, Florida andTexas; and 90s to 105 degrees across the desert Southwest.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EDT time ranged from 42degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 86 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.   Other reports were unavailable from the National Weather Service.</TEXT></DOC>